## Verify the MQTT Sparkplug pipeline ({{ mqtt.broker }})

This stack seeds the Cirrus Link Transmission/Engine connections fully: each
edge gateway's Transmission and the central gateway's Engine boot already
pointed at `{{ mqtt.broker_url }}` with their Sparkplug identity set, so the
pipeline forms with no UI clicks. This step is a verification, not a manual
procedure - confirm the flow came up, and reach for the manual steps below only
if it did not.

The Cirrus modules install from the project's `modules/cache/`, which starts
empty. Populate it once before bringing the stack up:

```sh
ignition-stack modules download {{ mqtt.modules }}
docker compose up -d
```

What to check:
{% if mqtt.engine_gateways %}
{%- for gw in mqtt.engine_gateways %}
- **Engine on {{ gw.name }}** ({{ gw.url }}): Config -> MQTT Engine -> Servers shows
  the seeded server `{{ mqtt.broker_url }}` as **Connected**, and the Engine tag
  tree lists each edge node below.
{%- endfor %}
{% endif %}
{%- if mqtt.transmission_gateways %}
{%- for gw in mqtt.transmission_gateways %}
- **Transmission on {{ gw.name }}** ({{ gw.url }}): Config -> MQTT Transmission ->
  Servers shows `{{ mqtt.broker_url }}` **Connected**, publishing as
  **Group ID `{{ gw.group_id }}` / Edge Node ID `{{ gw.edge_node_id }}`**.
{%- endfor %}
{% endif %}
- **Broker ({{ mqtt.broker }})**: its web UI lists the connected MQTT clients and
  the live Sparkplug topics (`spBv1.0/{{ project_name }}/...`).

> **Two trial caveats (demo posture).** The Cirrus Transmission/Engine modules
> run on Ignition's ~2-hour platform trial - a gateway/container restart resets
> it. The {{ mqtt.broker }} broker itself needs an active license to open its
> MQTT listener; this stack's `{{ mqtt.broker }}-trial` init container starts the
> trial automatically over the broker's REST API on every `up`. For a real
> deployment, set a `LICENSE_TYPE` / license env on the broker and drop the
> trial init.
{% elif mqtt and (mqtt.transmission_gateways or mqtt.engine_gateways) %}
## Link the gateway to the MQTT broker ({{ service }})

{{ reason }}

This stack wires a Sparkplug pipeline through the **{{ mqtt.broker }}** broker.
Only chariot's seeded connection was verified live, so for this broker the MQTT
connections are set by hand - the steps below are pre-filled with this stack's
identities so you only have to copy them in. The broker endpoint is
`{{ mqtt.broker_url }}` (reachable from each gateway container by the broker's
compose service name).

> The Cirrus Link Transmission/Engine modules run a ~2-hour trial that resets on
> every gateway restart, so this loop demos with no license.

The Cirrus modules install from the project's `modules/cache/`, which starts
empty. Populate it once before the modules will load, then bring the stack up:

```sh
ignition-stack modules download {{ mqtt.modules }}
docker compose up -d
```

The bootstrap copies whatever is in `modules/cache/` into each gateway on first
boot; if the modules are missing, fill the cache and re-run `docker compose up -d`.
{% if mqtt.engine_gateways %}
**MQTT Engine** - subscribes to the broker and aggregates; typically zero config
beyond the server entry:
{% for gw in mqtt.engine_gateways %}
- On **{{ gw.name }}** ({{ gw.url }}): Config -> MQTT Engine -> Settings ->
  Servers, add a server pointing at `{{ mqtt.broker_url }}`. Engine subscribes to
  all Sparkplug groups on `spBv1.0` by default, so once the server connects no
  further setup is needed.
{% endfor %}
{% endif %}
{% if mqtt.transmission_gateways %}
**MQTT Transmission** - publishes Sparkplug; one Edge Node per gateway:
{% for gw in mqtt.transmission_gateways %}
- On **{{ gw.name }}** ({{ gw.url }}): Config -> MQTT Transmission -> Settings ->
  Servers, add a server pointing at `{{ mqtt.broker_url }}`. Then set this node's
  Sparkplug identity - **Group ID = `{{ gw.group_id }}`** and
  **Edge Node ID = `{{ gw.edge_node_id }}`**.
{% endfor %}
{% endif %}
**Copy from `.env`** (broker credentials/ports):
{% for key, value in env_vars %}
- `{{ key }}` = `{{ value }}`
{%- endfor %}
{% else %}
